Function for calculating route distance

  • We need the function to calculate the route distance we developed in the prior code:
# write function to calculate the distance for a single route (i'th route)
path_dist_func <-
  function(pathVec,distMat) {
    temp_mat_path <- 
      rbind(pathVec[-length(pathVec)],
            pathVec[-1])
    dist <- sum(apply(X = temp_mat_path,
                      MARGIN = 2,
                      FUN = function(x) distMat[x[1],x[2]]))
    return(dist)
}

Random Paramater Space Searching

  • Let’s say we are interested in identifying the shortest path to visit 20 FQHC’s
  • We cannot search the full parameter space, it would take too long:
factorial(20)/2
## [1] 1.216451e+18
  • that is 1.2 quintillion numbers to search. If you could search 1000 combinations per second, it would still take you:
n_calculations <- factorial(20)/2
seconds <- n_calculations/1000
seconds_in_a_year <- 60*60*24*365
years <- seconds/seconds_in_a_year
years
## [1] 38573408

38 million years.

  • We could consider simply randomly searching the parameter space for some amount of time to see how far we get!
  • Let’s first identify the subset of 20 sites
## instead of searching every solution, let's just search some of the solution space. 
## start with random search? 
## 100 random paths using 20 sites:
## subset to 20

  • Finally, let’s implement code to randomly sample 2k paths to search:
## generate random list of 2k paths to search (using all 20 sites): 
set.seed(32)
## one at a time
sample(sites20$OBJECTID,replace=F,size=20)
##  [1] "6"  "11" "9"  "18" "8"  "1"  "7"  "19" "3"  "20" "15" "14" "2"  "10" "12"
## [16] "17" "5"  "16" "4"  "13"
sample(sites20$OBJECTID,replace=F,size=20)
##  [1] "6"  "5"  "3"  "8"  "19" "9"  "10" "14" "13" "12" "16" "11" "4"  "7"  "20"
## [16] "17" "1"  "15" "2"  "18"
## Now do 2k
paths_1k <- 
  unique(t(sapply(1:2000,
           function(x) sample(sites20$OBJECTID,replace=F,size=20))))
  • Now that we have generated 2k random paths, we can calculate the distance for each path and find the minimum distance:
## calculate distances for these paths
paths_1k_df <- data.table(paths_1k)
## find minimum
paths_1k_df$distance <- 
  apply(paths_1k,
            MARGIN = 1,
            FUN = path_dist_func, 
            distMat = dist_mat20)
paths_1k_df[distance == min(distance)]
##    V1 V2 V3 V4 V5 V6 V7 V8 V9 V10 V11 V12 V13 V14 V15 V16 V17 V18 V19 V20
## 1: 18  7 17 19 16  5 20 14 10  15   9   3   6   4   2  11   8   1  12  13
##    distance
## 1: 1740.999
  • We can visualize our answers with a graph:
## create graph of our answers:
paths_1k_df[,id:=1:.N]
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(paths_1k_df,aes(x=id,y=distance)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept=min(paths_1k_df$distance),color='red')

Genetic Algorithms

  • A better metaheuristic to use is a genetic algorithm. We can use the GA package in R to solve these sorts of problems.
  • Since this function will maximize rather than minimize, I define the objective function (fitness function) as 1/cost (so max is the min cost)
## Implement a genetic algorithm!
## must add fitness function to maximize, inverse of route distance (since we want to minimize distance)
library(GA)
## Loading required package: foreach
## Loading required package: iterators
## Package 'GA' version 3.2
## Type 'citation("GA")' for citing this R package in publications.
## 
## Attaching package: 'GA'
## The following object is masked from 'package:utils':
## 
##     de
Fitness_f <- 
  function(pathVec,...) 1/path_dist_func(pathVec, ...)
gaobj <- ga(type = "permutation", fitness = Fitness_f, 
         distMat = dist_mat20,lower = 1, upper = 20,
         popSize = 10, maxiter = 1000, run = 100, pmutation = 0.2)
  • We can summarize the path the GA has taken, and graph the fitness of the population at every generation
## summarize results
summary(gaobj)

## extract best solution
gaobj@solution

## extract fitness of best solution
1/gaobj@fitnessValue
## [1] 992.7153
  • Then we can run the solution through our code to calculate the distance. Did the GA do better than our random search?
## check we get the same answer
path1 <- 
  as.character(gaobj@solution[1,])
path_dist_func(path1,dist_mat20) # Yes!
## [1] 992.7153
